AGI - It is a friendship with strong asymmetries between Russia and China after the Russian invasion of Ukraine. Moscow is struggling with Western sanctions and the loss of European customers for gas and oil, Beijing counteracting duties, and have just arrived with new ones, imposed by the US on chip components and electric cars.
&nbsp;
As soon as he was installed again, Putin flew from Xi Jinping for the second time in just over a year. Renewed the friendship that however sees the position of Beijing ever stronger. In 2023 bilateral trade between the two countries reached the record figure of 240 billion dollars. According to an analysis by Alexandra Prokopenko, Alexander Kolyandr and Denis Kasyanchuk for The Bell, Russia has progressively abandoned the dollar and euro in its commercial transactions, adopting more and more the yuan. Before invading Ukraine, exchanges in Chinese currency to the Moscow stock exchange were almost zero, today are more than a third: "Last December, 35.8% of Russian exports were paid in yuan, along with 37% of import."
&nbsp;
And if China continues to provide materials and products from double-use, civil and military, the meeting was closed by Putin's statement on the search for a "political solution" to war in Ukraine. Russian President Vladimir Putin rejects accusations of not wanting to negotiate a solution for the Ukrainian crisis: "We have never rejected the negotiations and we are closely following the preparation of the Geneva Summit," he said in China.
&nbsp;
Today he is back on the theme: "After Western deception, we have to figure out who we can deal with." As for China, where it is for the second day of a mission that has seen it very close to Beijing, "he sincerely seeks to solve the problem of Ukraine", he noted.<br> From the point of view of Beijing it is necessary to close the war and sanctions before they become an excessive burden on the economic recovery of Europe, which remains a very important market for Chinese products.

