AGI - In a field hospital that became one of the major traumatological centers in Gaza, a doctor who worked in a dozen war zones described the situation as the most "catastrophic" I have ever seen. "It is devastating," said Javed Ali>, head of the International Medical Corps for emergency interventions in Gaza, interviewed by the Afp agency.
The man, speaking from a field hospital to the northwest of the areas of Rafah evacuated from Israel, said that the situation around the city to the far south is "terrible". The hospital, in the coastal area of Al-Mawasi that Israel has designated as "humanitarian zone", has become in a few months in a structure with more than 150 beds, consisting of numerous white tents and containers.
&nbsp;
Since the first orders of evacuation for Rafah were issued on 6 May, in view of a fearful invasion of land of the southernmost part of Gaza, almost half of the 1.4 million people who had taken refuge have left, according to UN agencies. "There was a massive movement of individuals," Ali said, adding that most avoided Al-Mawasi, who was already dramatically overcrowded, instead heading towards the city of Khan Yunis, marked by the war, which was a battlefield until last month. Those who arrive are "exused, frightened, have no resources>", said Ali, adding that many patients ask "money, support... to be able to transfer their families safely.»
